   (Message) ROOT CAUSE: `program.cpp:12` uses `for (Node *cur = head; cur !=
   nullptr; cur = cur->next)` while the loop body at `program.cpp:13` executes
   `delete cur;`. In the observed run, `main` creates `a = 0x502000000050` with
   `a->next = b = 0x502000000030`, `b->next = c = 0x502000000010`, and `c->next
   = nullptr`; `destroy_list(a)` starts with `head`/`cur` pointing at `a`. The
   first loop body deletes `cur`, freeing the storage for node `a`; then the
   `for` loop increment expression evaluates `cur->next` to advance to `b`, but
   `cur` still points to the already-freed node `a`, so reading `cur->next` is a
   heap-use-after-free. The bug is not that the list contents are wrong; the
   `next` pointer was valid before deletion, but the code waits until after
   `delete cur` to read it.
   
   LOCAL FIX: Save the next pointer before deleting the current node, then
   advance using the saved value rather than dereferencing freed memory. For
   example, replace `destroy_list` with: `static void destroy_list(Node *head) {
   for (Node *cur = head; cur != nullptr; ) { Node *next = cur->next; delete
   cur; cur = next; } }`. As a diff: `- for (Node *cur = head; cur != nullptr;
   cur = cur->next) { delete cur; }` / `+ for (Node *cur = head; cur != nullptr;
   ) { Node *next = cur->next; delete cur; cur = next; }`.
   
   GLOBAL FIX: Avoid manual raw-pointer ownership for linked-list nodes and
   encode ownership in the type, e.g. make `next` a `std::unique_ptr<Node>` and
   let recursive/RAII destruction release the chain automatically, or wrap the
   list in a container class whose destructor owns the traversal invariant. That
   design prevents this class of bug because client code no longer performs
   “delete then continue traversing through the deleted object”; ownership
   transfer and destruction order are centralized and enforced by the type
   system.
